{"cursor":"12715","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox writer\n| name = Andrew Robinson image = image_size = alt = caption = birth_name =\n| birth_date = 1957 birth_place = England death_date = death_place =\n| body_discovered = death_cause = resting_place = resting_place_coordinates =\n| residence = London, United Kingdom nationality = British ethnicity = English\n| citizenship = United Kingdom other_names = known_for = education = Dragon\n| School Eton College alma_mater = University College, Oxford School of\n| Oriental and African Studies employer = News International notableworks =\n| Satyajit Ray: The Inner Eye (1989), The Art of Rabindranath Tagore (1989), The\n| Man Who Deciphered Linear B: The Story of Michael Ventris (2002), The Last Man\n| Who Knew Everything: Thomas Young (2006), The Story of Measurement (2007),\n| Writing and Script (2009). occupation = Writer years_active = home_town =\n| London religion = spouse = partner = children = parents = Neville\n| Robinson Daphne Robinson relations = awards = signature = signature_alt =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'W. Andrew Robinson' (born 1957) is a British\nauthor [http://www.librarything.com/author/robinsonandrew Andrew Robinson\n(1)], LibraryThing. [http://www.alibris.com/search/books/author/Robin-\nson,%20Andrew Books by Andrew Robinson], Alibris. and former newspaper\neditor. Mark Twaite, [http://www.bookdepository.co.uk/interview/with/author/andrew-\nrobinson Interview with Andrew Robinson], [[The Book Depository]], 2009.\n\nAndrew Robinson was educated at the Dragon School, Eton College where he was a\nKing's Scholar, University College, Oxford where he read Chemistry and finally\nthe School of Oriental and African Studies in London. He is the son of Neville\nRobinson, an Oxford physicist.\n\nRobinson first visited India in 1975 and has been a devotee of the country's\nculture ever since, in particular the Bengali poet and philosopher Rabindranath\nTagore and the Bengali film director Satyajit Ray. He has authored many books\nand articles. Until 2006, he was the Literary Editor of the [[Times Higher\nEducation Supplement]]. He has also been a Visiting Fellow at Wolfson College,\nCambridge. Anna Jones, [http://www.wolfson.cam.ac.uk/news/2009/10/23/cambridge-festival-of-ideas-\npodcast/ Cambridge Festival of Ideas podcast],\n[http://www.wolfson.cam.ac.uk/news/ News], Wolfson College, Cambridge, UK, 23\nOctober 2009. He is based in London and is now a full-time writer.\n","linknr":287,"url":"W._Andrew_Robinson","recorded":1376418633,"links":["/w/index.php?title=W._Andrew_Robinson&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=W._Andrew_Robinson&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._Andrew_Robinson","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/England","/wiki/United_Kingdom","/wiki/Dragon_School","/wiki/Eton_College","/wiki/University_College,_Oxford","/wiki/School_of_Oriental_and_African_Studies","/wiki/United_Kingdom","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-interview-3","/wiki/Dragon_School","/wiki/Eton_College","/wiki/King%27s_Scholar","/wiki/University_C